{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VrUHFMriZP2WYNzHTcqvW2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `repository-s3` module is already included in Elasticsearch 8.x as a built-in module (not a plugin). This is great!\n\nNow I need to:\n1. Create the `es-secure-settings` Secret with MinIO credentials for the keystore\n2. Add these credentials to the Elasticsearch keystore on each node\n3. Register the snapshot repository\n4. Create a snapshot\n\nThe approach for adding credentials securely (without placing them in elasticsearch.yml or env vars):\n\n**Elasticsearch Keystore** is the right way. The keystore stores sensitive settings like S3 access keys. The keys would be:\n- `s3.client.default.access_key` = `minioadmin`\n- `s3.client.default.secret_key` = `minioadmin`\n\nFor the keystore approach with a Kubernetes Secret, I can create the secret with the credentials, then use the `elasticsearch-keystore` command to add these values to the keystore on each node by executing into the pods. After that, I'll use the hot-reload API to reload the secure settings without needing a restart. This is the Elasticsearch recommended way to handle sensitive settings without putting them in elasticsearch.yml.\n\nSince the pods are already running, I'll create the `es-secure-settings` Secret first, then exec into each Elasticsearch node and add the keys to the keystore, and finally call the reload endpoint to apply the changes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":402,"cache_read_input_tokens":33988,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":402},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2fcdfef7-30f2-4e5b-9b00-102e91aa0193","uuid":"db617c1e-39ee-4f57-8ca8-99dc99